Wash and dry produce.

Dice @potatoes{12%oz} into 1⁄2-inch pieces. Drain @corn{1} and pat dry with #paper towels{}.

Dice @onion{1}(diced into 1⁄2-inch pieces).

Pick leaves from @cilantro{1/4%oz}; mince stems.

Quarter @lime{1}.

Reserve 1⁄4 tsp @ancho chili powder{1%tsp} in a #small bowl{} (you'll use it in Step 4).

Place potatoes in a #medium bowl{} with 1 TBSP water. Cover tightly with #plastic wrap{} and microwave until slightly tender, ~{5-7%minutes}. (They'll finish cooking in the soup.)

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pot{} over medium-high heat.

Add corn, onion, and cilantro stems. Cook, stirring occasionally, until onion is softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add @garlic powder{1%tsp}, remaining chili powder, and 1/4 tsp @sugar{}. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add potatoes (careful when uncovering the bowl—steam may release!), @veggie stock concentrate{2}, 1 1⁄2 cups water, and 1⁄2 tsp @salt{} to pot.

Bring soup to a boil, then reduce heat to low and cover. Simmer until soup has thickened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Turn off heat; stir in @cream sauce base{4%oz}, half the @cotija cheese{1/2%cup}, 1 TBSP @butter{}, and a squeeze of lime juice.

Divide soup between #bowls{}; top with reserved chili powder, remaining cotija, cilantro leaves, @pepitas{1/2%oz}, and a squeeze of lime juice. Serve with remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Mexican street food inspired this creamy corn and potato chowder - perfect for any night of the week!